{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626577"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:39:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:39:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17082"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17082"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.16,0.02,0.16,0.51]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9772"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70406"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9772","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9772"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17082"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55870"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"5254"},{"type":"tags","id":"5256"},{"type":"tags","id":"10824"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22950"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23095"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70406"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECarbapenems are an important class of broad-spectrum antibiotics used to treat severe infections.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes their mechanism of action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Interferes with bacterial folate synthesis","Disrupts bacterial cell membrane integrity","Blocks bacterial DNA gyrase enzyme","Inhibits bacterial protein synthesis at the 50S ribosomal subunit","Binds to penicillin-binding proteins and inhibits cell wall synthesis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECarbapenems bind\u003Cstrong\u003E penicillin-binding proteins and inhibit cell wall synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E. Like other beta-lactam antibiotics, they prevent proper peptidoglycan cross-linking in the bacterial cell wall, leading to lysis of the cell.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterferes with bacterial folate synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E represents the mechanism of action of sulfonamides and trimethoprim.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisrupts bacterial cell membrane integrity\u003C/strong\u003E describes how polymyxins and daptomycin work.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks bacterial DNA gyrase enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism by which fluoroquinolones exert their antimicrobial effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits bacterial protein synthesis at the 50S ribosomal subunit\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of action of macrolides and lincosamides.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECarbapenems are particularly valuable because they are resistant to most beta-lactamases, including extended-spectrum beta-lactamases (ESBLs). They have broad activity against gram-positive, gram-negative and anaerobic bacteria.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Carbapenems are broad-spectrum beta-lactam antibiotics resistant to most beta-lactamases.","Carbapenems work by binding to penicillin-binding proteins to inhibit bacterial cell wall synthesis.","Carbapenems have activity against most gram-positive, gram-negative and anaerobic bacteria."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55870"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17082"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55870"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-14T22:28:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T22:29:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9772"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70406"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"